<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#F0DCA0">Originally posted by Dante on 01-14-2000 08:57 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I agree magic items (or at least the unique items - powerful and with a name) should be very rare. It gives you really a kick if you find somewhere in a dungeon or in an old chest on the *****k of the museum an item that radiates magic like hell (but nobody noticed that before you did) AND that turns out to be useful for your quest as well. Wohow!

I agree with Goemoe in that magical spells and items should not be too powerful (like the AD&D fireball example) unless perhaps near the end of the game where magic could be the only way to make the difference (cfr. Ultima where the spells of the 8th circle include Armageddon and the like...). This could be the drive for players to not to neglect a magical carreer.

It all depends on which evolution the game designer wants to put in the main character. E.g.: in Diablo, all player types were balanced very well: to defeat Diablo, you could do it as good as being a fighter, a rogue or a mage, BUT you needed to specialise. Project-C could on the other hand favorise players that are multi disciplined and require good fighting skills AND good magic skills to be able to win the final battle. An pure fighter (zero mage skills) would face the impossible to solve the last problem. Perhaps that magical items here could help the him out, but what then for the super mage-zero fighter? What compensation could he get? Perhaps he needs a follower (NPC friend) to do the hacking for him?

Perhaps it is a good idea that the main character has something special (players like that  :)) in that he is the only creature on the world that can attain expert skill levels in BOTH fighting AND magic. E.g. you are the most dreaded fighter on the surface of the earth AND at the same time you are so bloody powerful in magic that you can resurrect slain enemies.

Imagine a story line with a charismatic leader that is cursed by some evil force, causing him to be evil. This curse cannot be removed - by death only. But you need this guy for some very important information and hence need to cure him from his curse. To make things complete - he once was the king's best fighter (paladin, whatever) and he has never been beaten in fight before.

The answer is: YOU kill him. YOU resurrect him. Needed: a super fighter-super mage.

All this are just ideas. And I prefer to kill my enemy by MY hand, and to resurrect him by MY spell. NOT via using some magical item.

So i guess, magical items should exist in two categories:
- the common stuff (exercices of the great enchanter - mages to learn their skills): can be found rather occasionally. Helps you a bit further, increases your skills here and there.
- the VERY RARE stuff. Items of exceptional gifts, with a story, a history and of which you feel that it wuld be a loss for the world if you break them/use them up/...

Well, it seems I mixed up some things but I hope its interesting.

Peace be with you,
Dante.

Perhaps magic should be more powerful than plain fighting, just for the reason mentioned above. And of course, usually, learning magic is more difficult that learning to wear armor and to wield a weapon.

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
